INSERT INTO news_stories (id, record_id, url, body_text, ai_summary) VALUES ('bb16d4c5-97cc-4410-b622-f7b5b627b89b', '03a7f376-fa4e-4771-ae7c-07c17f7d1f24', 'https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/eric-john-shestalo-vehicle-found-1.6530245', 'ContentSkip to Main ContentAccessibility HelpMenuWhen search suggestions are available use up and down arrows to review and enter to select.SearchSearchSign InQuick LinksNewsSportsRadioMusicListen LiveTVWatchnewsTop StoriesLocalClimateWorldCanadaPoliticsIndigenousOpinionThe NationalBusinessHealthEntertainmentScienceCBC News InvestigatesGo PublicAbout CBC NewsBeing Black in CanadaMore Investigators find Chilliwack double-homicide suspect&#39;s vehicle on Friday | CBC News LoadedBritish ColumbiaInvestigators find Chilliwack double-homicide suspect&#39;s vehicle on FridayHomicide investigators say they have found the vehicle that was driven by Eric John Shestalo, who allegedly shot and killed two women in Chilliwack, B.C. on Thursday.Eric John Shestalo, 50, is still at large and considered dangerous after Thursday shootingCBC News  · Posted: Jul 23, 2022 1:27 PM EDT | Last Updated: July 23, 2022Police released this photo of Eric John Shestalo Thursday evening, along with his jeep. Investigators say they have now found his jeep, but he remains at large. (Integrated Homicide Investigation Team)Homicide investigators say they have found the vehicle that was driven by Eric John Shestalo, who allegedly shot and killed two women in Chilliwack, B.C. on Thursday.Shestalo, 50, is still at large and considered armed and dangerous, according to the Integrated Homicide Investigation Team (IHIT).He was last seen driving a red 1990 Jeep YJ, with a yellow front, on Thursday, after a triple shooting at a home in the 9700 block of McNaught Road, near Yale Road, just east of downtown Chilliwack around 11 a.m. PT Thursday.Police said they located the jeep in nearby Bridal Falls on Friday. One man was also injured in the Thursday shooting, but his injuries were not life-threatening, according to police.Police tape is stretched across the 9700 block of McNaught Road in Chilliwack following reports of a shooting around 11 a.m. Thursday. (CBC News)&#34;Investigators are in the process of determining why Mr. Shestalo travelled to Bridal Falls. We&#39;re working to determine if he remains in the area or if he left,&#34; said Sgt. Timothy Pierotti in a statement.Police said the public should exercise caution if they spot Shestalo. People are urged to call 911 and not to approach him.Police hunt &#39;armed and dangerous&#39; suspect after 2 killed, 1 wounded in Chilliwack shootingHe&#39;s described as a white man, standing five feet nine inches tall and weighing 176 pounds. He was last seen wearing black pants, a black jacket and a black hat with orange rim.Police said Shestalo knew the victims and the shooting is believed to be targeted. They&#39;re asking for public assistance as they try and find Shestalo.Anyone who was in Bridal Falls between 11 a.m. on Thursday and 10 a.m. on Friday, and has dashcam footage or information about the case, is asked to contact IHIT at 1-877-551-4448 or through email at ihitinfo@rcmp-grc.gc.ca.With files from Liam Britten and Ali PitargueCBC&#39;s Journalistic Standards and Practices|About CBC NewsCorrections and clarifications|Submit a news tip|Report errorRelated Stories Top stories from British Columbia Why these two East Vancouver residents are distributing thousands of N95 masks for free He made history as the NHL&#39;s first Black official. Now he&#39;s joining the B.C. Hockey Hall of Fame Abuse and harassment survivors &#39;silenced&#39; by non-disclosure agreements fight for change to B.C. lawFooter LinksMy AccountProfileCBC GemNewslettersAbout CBC AccountsConnect with CBCFacebookTwitterYouTubeInstagramMobileRSSPodcastsContact CBCSubmit FeedbackHelp CentreAudience Relations, CBC P.O. Box 500 Station A Toronto, ON  Canada, M5W 1E6 Toll-free (Canada only):  1-866-306-4